VLN Analysis for prediction of Pathogenic / Benign

David McGaughey

September 7, 2016

R Markdown

Analysis of the performance of VLN (variant lanscape numbers, 100bp window, GRCh38) in categorizing ClinVar pathogenic against benign variants. CADD used as the gold standard to compare performance.

# gather/melt

So.pathogenic seems to generally have a higher VLN than the benign. Which is opposite my initial finding. And our expectation. What is going on here? The answer is very simple, but it took me a while to figure out. Lets pull in ensembls clinvar_only variant set, and remake the plot (this is what was used for the Molecular Rounds fig in August) and see the summary stats.

# recreate the density plot we've seen before:
clinOnly_vcf %>% filter(Status!='Conflicting', Status!='Other') %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=VLN100all, colour=Status))+geom_density() + theme_Publication() + coord_cartesian(xlim=c(0,100))

# summary stats, as above:
clinOnly_vcf %>% gather(.,VLN,Value,-V1,-V2,-V3,-V4,-V5,-V6,-V7,-V8,-ClinSig,-Status) %>% group_by(VLN, Status) %>% filter(Status!='Conflicting', Status!='Other') %>% summarise(mean(Value), median(Value),`25th_percentile`=quantile(Value,0.25),`75th_percentile`=quantile(Value,0.75),Total=n())

OK, the plot looks the same. BUT: What immediately pops out is how FEW benign variants there are. Did I screw up the filtering?

# checking number of benign (of ANY kind) in original vcf
orig_clin %>% filter(grepl('benign',V8)) %>% nrow()
## [1] 1238

1238.so for some reason there are VERY VERY few benigns.

I then downloaded the latest clinvar vcf from NCBIs ftp site: ftp://ftp.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pub/clinvar/ clinvar_20160831.vcf.gz

New density plot, which should look like the density plot from Augusts molecular rounds

# let's make a new density plot
clinOnly_vcf_latest %>% filter(ClinSig %in% c(2,5)) %>% mutate(Status=ifelse(ClinSig==2,'Benign','Pathogenic')) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=VLN100all, colour=Status))+geom_density() + theme_Publication() + coord_cartesian(xlim=c(0,100))

# summary stats
clinOnly_vcf_latest %>% filter(ClinSig %in% c(2,5)) %>% mutate(Status=ifelse(ClinSig==2,'Benign','Pathogenic')) %>% 
  gather(.,VLN,Value,-V1,-V2,-V3,-V4,-V5,-V6,-V7,-V8,-ClinSig,-Status) %>% 
  group_by(VLN, Status) %>% summarise(mean(Value), median(Value),quantile(Value,0.25),quantile(Value,0.75),Total=n())

OK.now we have 30,000 benign variants So, unfortunately I used a poor data set for my first pass analysis. Not sure what ensembl did or is doing. Got unlucky as 800 isnt that small, but apparently it was not representative. I did a lot of work (not shown) comparing variants with highMAF (>0.05) and lowerMAF (<0.01) and they have very similar characteristics (in VLN scoring) to the clinvar benign.

Well, lets proceed since Ive done 95% of the hard work and see whether the VLN numbers have any ability to distinguish benign from pathogenic variants

Keep your expectations low. very low.

First lets see how well CADD does Since CADD did a ROC test on higher MAF variants vs clinvar pathogenic in their paper, Ill do the same

# plot ROC, which shows performance against 50/50 guessing
ggplot(glm_caddOnly_roc,aes(x=X1,y=X2)) + geom_line() + theme_Publication() + xlab('') + ylab('') + geom_abline() + ggtitle("CADD-only Predictive ROC")

# CADD's auc (1 is perfect, 0 is worthless) is 0.92. Very good
auc.tmp <- performance(pred,"auc"); as.numeric(auc.tmp@y.values)
## [1] 0.9243615

CADDs auc (1 is perfect, 0.5 is a monkey flipping coins) is 0.92. Very good

Lets see if the ROC/AUC improves by adding the VLN to the CADD

# yeah....not helping much
ggplot(both,aes(x=X1,y=X2,colour=Data)) + geom_line() + theme_Publication() + xlab('') + ylab('') + geom_abline() + ggtitle("CADD and CADD-VLN Predictive ROC")

# auc is virtually identical, after adding VLN to the predictor
auc.tmp <- performance(pred,"auc"); as.numeric(auc.tmp@y.values)
## [1] 0.9248127

Uh, no. Not at all.

Lets quickly see how VLN does ALONE as a predictor

# not so hot
ggplot(triple,aes(x=X1,y=X2,colour=Data)) + geom_line() + theme_Publication() + xlab('') + ylab('') + geom_abline() + ggtitle("CADD and CADD-VLN and VLN Predictive ROC")

# also bad
auc.tmp <- performance(pred,"auc"); as.numeric(auc.tmp@y.values)
## [1] 0.5198679

Well crap.

# still not so hot
ggplot(quad,aes(x=X1,y=X2,colour=Data)) + geom_line() + theme_Publication() + xlab('') + ylab('') + geom_abline() + ggtitle("CADD and CADD-VLN and VLN Predictive ROC")

Summary? This isnt working. We could try doing VLN with CADD scores to see whether the idea of regional or landscape genome variation has any merit. Its possible that straight up counts is a crappy metric.
